WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.021
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:05.021 --> 00:00:05.520
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:05.520 --> 00:00:08.470
SPEAKER 1: With that very
humbling introduction

00:00:08.470 --> 00:00:11.330
let's get a round of
applause for Bobby Braun.

00:00:11.330 --> 00:00:12.720
BOBBY BRAUN: Wow.

00:00:12.720 --> 00:00:13.980
I'd like to meet that guy.

00:00:13.980 --> 00:00:16.320
He sounds really impressive.

00:00:16.320 --> 00:00:17.520
Thank you.

00:00:17.520 --> 00:00:20.670
First of all, thanks to
Google for hosting all of us

00:00:20.670 --> 00:00:22.100
here today.

00:00:22.100 --> 00:00:25.840
The campus that you're building
here in Boulder is beautiful.

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:29.170
And we're all very happy
to have you in our city

00:00:29.170 --> 00:00:31.380
and in our state.

00:00:31.380 --> 00:00:33.240
As was said, my
name is Bobby Braun.

00:00:33.240 --> 00:00:35.190
And I'm the dean of the
College of Engineering

00:00:35.190 --> 00:00:38.580
and Applied Science at the
University of Colorado Boulder.

00:00:38.580 --> 00:00:42.090
We are among the fastest
growing engineering colleges,

00:00:42.090 --> 00:00:45.300
and we're actually one of
the most diverse colleges

00:00:45.300 --> 00:00:47.070
of engineering in the country.

00:00:47.070 --> 00:00:49.890
And that's something that we're
really proud about because it

00:00:49.890 --> 00:00:53.880
allows us to reach out and
partner more with industry

00:00:53.880 --> 00:00:57.420
in our state, including Google.

00:00:57.420 --> 00:00:59.790
I'm a Mars guy.

00:00:59.790 --> 00:01:04.170
I guess, maybe, a
Martian in my blood.

00:01:04.170 --> 00:01:06.450
And I've worked on a
number of NASA missions.

00:01:06.450 --> 00:01:09.400
And typically, I work with
engineers and scientists

00:01:09.400 --> 00:01:14.430
on what it's like to build
and send spacecraft to Mars.

00:01:14.430 --> 00:01:19.630
But today I'm here with a really
interesting group of people,

00:01:19.630 --> 00:01:22.260
people who I've had
the pleasure to work

00:01:22.260 --> 00:01:29.190
with for a number of years now
in what's been a groundbreaking

00:01:29.190 --> 00:01:31.410
television series
put on by National

00:01:31.410 --> 00:01:35.930
Geographic with executive
producers Ron Howard and Brian

00:01:35.930 --> 00:01:37.530
Grazer.

00:01:37.530 --> 00:01:40.050
And I got to tell you,
working with these people,

00:01:40.050 --> 00:01:42.690
it's been like a family.

00:01:42.690 --> 00:01:45.930
And for me as an engineer,
perhaps the best thing

00:01:45.930 --> 00:01:47.742
has been working with--

00:01:47.742 --> 00:01:48.825
not with other engineers--

00:01:48.825 --> 00:01:49.325
[LAUGHTER]

00:01:49.325 --> 00:01:53.175
--but with artists
and film studies

00:01:53.175 --> 00:01:58.170
folks, actors, writers,
and big thinkers

00:01:58.170 --> 00:02:01.860
from across the spectrum
that have been part

00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:04.230
of this innovative docudrama.

00:02:04.230 --> 00:02:07.560
How many of you have seen any
of the episodes, season one

00:02:07.560 --> 00:02:09.669
or season two?

00:02:09.669 --> 00:02:10.759
That's a good number.

00:02:10.759 --> 00:02:12.100
It's a good number.

00:02:12.100 --> 00:02:14.380
Season two is
going on right now.

00:02:14.380 --> 00:02:21.260
We just last night-- episode
four was premiered on Nat Geo.

00:02:21.260 --> 00:02:23.890
They're showing on
Monday nights, 9:00 PM.

00:02:23.890 --> 00:02:25.300
You can catch up with those.

00:02:25.300 --> 00:02:28.645
And you can actually
see episode five and six

00:02:28.645 --> 00:02:30.460
that have yet to come out.

00:02:30.460 --> 00:02:33.460
Tonight on our
campus at CU Boulder,

00:02:33.460 --> 00:02:35.860
we'll be premiering
episode five.

00:02:35.860 --> 00:02:39.940
You can see it on campus a
week before it will actually

00:02:39.940 --> 00:02:42.280
be shown worldwide.

00:02:42.280 --> 00:02:44.200
So that's what we're
all here today.

00:02:44.200 --> 00:02:46.600
We're here for this
event, and then

00:02:46.600 --> 00:02:49.420
for this evening's
event in Boulder.

00:02:49.420 --> 00:02:51.790
I'm here today
joined with a number

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:56.860
of the members of the show
in various capacities.

00:02:56.860 --> 00:03:02.720
Going from my--
going down this way--

00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:03.774
I always mess that up.

00:03:03.774 --> 00:03:04.940
STEPHEN PETRANEK: Your left.

00:03:04.940 --> 00:03:05.430
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:05.430 --> 00:03:06.350
BOBBY BRAUN: Well, it's my left.

00:03:06.350 --> 00:03:07.350
But it's their right.

00:03:07.350 --> 00:03:09.940
Let's do it that way.

00:03:09.940 --> 00:03:13.210
The person who corrects
me the most in my life

00:03:13.210 --> 00:03:16.600
is actually Stephen
Petranek, who over the years

00:03:16.600 --> 00:03:18.220
has been a great friend.

00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:22.220
Stephen is a co-executive
producer of the series.

00:03:22.220 --> 00:03:25.180
And in fact, the series
is based on a book

00:03:25.180 --> 00:03:29.230
that Stephen wrote years ago
about how we will actually live

00:03:29.230 --> 00:03:31.900
and settle the planet Mars.

00:03:31.900 --> 00:03:36.760
He's really the creative
genius behind the whole series,

00:03:36.760 --> 00:03:38.920
if you will, through his book.

00:03:38.920 --> 00:03:41.780
And it's wonderful to have
you here in Boulder today.

00:03:41.780 --> 00:03:44.740
Next to him is
Antonia Juhasz, who

00:03:44.740 --> 00:03:49.420
is an expert in oil
and energy policy

00:03:49.420 --> 00:03:52.990
and has written numerous papers
and given numerous forums

00:03:52.990 --> 00:03:54.670
on those topics.

00:03:54.670 --> 00:03:58.300
In this series,
she's a big thinker.

00:03:58.300 --> 00:04:00.910
So this is a series, right,
that goes back and forth

00:04:00.910 --> 00:04:03.830
between the present
and the future, right?

00:04:03.830 --> 00:04:07.280
So we talk about what's
happening in our world today,

00:04:07.280 --> 00:04:09.010
and then we flash
forward from that

00:04:09.010 --> 00:04:13.090
into how that might portray
into a human settlement of Mars

00:04:13.090 --> 00:04:14.310
in the future.

00:04:14.310 --> 00:04:18.130
Antonia has been wonderful
in providing insights

00:04:18.130 --> 00:04:21.680
about climate and
energy and policy,

00:04:21.680 --> 00:04:24.280
international policy
issues here on the Earth

00:04:24.280 --> 00:04:26.530
and how those might--
those same kind of issues

00:04:26.530 --> 00:04:28.850
might play out on Mars.

00:04:28.850 --> 00:04:32.830
And then next to her is actually
an award-winning writer,

00:04:32.830 --> 00:04:34.420
Leonard David.

00:04:34.420 --> 00:04:36.760
Who, if you're in the space
community like I am, Leonard

00:04:36.760 --> 00:04:39.410
needs no introductions.

00:04:39.410 --> 00:04:41.230
But Leonard has
written a book that

00:04:41.230 --> 00:04:45.490
is a companion book to the
National Geographic series.

00:04:45.490 --> 00:04:49.110
If you're interested, you can
pick one up on the back table

00:04:49.110 --> 00:04:50.560
there.

00:04:50.560 --> 00:04:54.640
But Leonard's book is a great
companion to the series.

00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:57.730
It provides wonderful
context about past, present,

00:04:57.730 --> 00:05:01.180
and future Mars exploration.

00:05:01.180 --> 00:05:02.650
And so we're here today.

00:05:02.650 --> 00:05:04.191
What we're going to
do is we're going

00:05:04.191 --> 00:05:08.050
to watch the trailer
from season one,

00:05:08.050 --> 00:05:10.480
just to bring you up to
speed about what happened

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:15.700
two years ago during season one,
which took place in the 2030s.

00:05:15.700 --> 00:05:18.670
Then we're going to show
the trailer for season two.

00:05:18.670 --> 00:05:20.620
Before I do, there's
two other folks

00:05:20.620 --> 00:05:23.200
I definitely want to
introduce very quickly--

00:05:23.200 --> 00:05:26.900
in the audience, who will be
speaking tonight on campus.

00:05:26.900 --> 00:05:30.860
And they're actors in
the Nat Geo series.

00:05:30.860 --> 00:05:32.260
And that's Sammi Rotibi--

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:33.910
maybe, Sammi, you
want to stand up--

00:05:33.910 --> 00:05:35.221
--and Evan Hall.

00:05:35.221 --> 00:05:39.380
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:39.380 --> 00:05:43.750
And as someone who's
consulted on the show

00:05:43.750 --> 00:05:45.760
and worked with
some of the writers

00:05:45.760 --> 00:05:48.470
and actors in the
production of the show,

00:05:48.470 --> 00:05:52.160
you know, they've
been fantastic.

00:05:52.160 --> 00:05:55.420
These guys-- it's just
their roles are so--

00:05:55.420 --> 00:05:59.330
it's amazing how well they've
suited into these roles.

00:05:59.330 --> 00:06:01.680
I know they each have an
engineering background,

00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:04.180
and you know, you have
multiple engineering degrees

00:06:04.180 --> 00:06:05.150
from CU Boulder.

00:06:05.150 --> 00:06:07.810
I'm just kidding.

00:06:07.810 --> 00:06:09.970
But from watching
you all on the show,

00:06:09.970 --> 00:06:12.870
I mean, one would
think that you did.

00:06:12.870 --> 00:06:14.996
And it's actually amazing.

00:06:14.996 --> 00:06:17.162
SPEAKER 2: I spoke to you
before the season started.

00:06:17.162 --> 00:06:17.520
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:17.520 --> 00:06:18.269
BOBBY BRAUN: Yeah.

00:06:18.269 --> 00:06:20.810
So it's been a lot
of back and forth,

00:06:20.810 --> 00:06:22.036
getting ready to do that.

00:06:22.036 --> 00:06:23.410
But that's what's
made this show,

00:06:23.410 --> 00:06:28.060
I think, so unique is that it's
a scientifically honest show.

00:06:28.060 --> 00:06:31.300
It's a scientifically
accurate portrayal

00:06:31.300 --> 00:06:33.910
of what the future
might look like

00:06:33.910 --> 00:06:40.010
based on what's happening
right now in space exploration.

00:06:40.010 --> 00:06:42.920
So what we do is
jump into the clips.

00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:44.410
The first-- this is season one.

00:06:44.410 --> 00:06:45.076
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:06:45.076 --> 00:06:47.560
- Mars will be risky, dangerous.

00:06:47.560 --> 00:06:50.812
But it'll be the greatest
adventure ever, ever

00:06:50.812 --> 00:06:51.520
in human history.

00:06:51.520 --> 00:06:53.530
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:06:53.530 --> 00:06:55.140
- Funny thing about Mars--

00:06:55.140 --> 00:06:56.860
it feels like Earth.

00:06:56.860 --> 00:07:00.494
But it is more hostile to
life than any place on Earth.

00:07:00.494 --> 00:07:00.993
- Ignition.

00:07:06.560 --> 00:07:09.970
- In the absence of gravity,
lots of things can go wrong.

00:07:09.970 --> 00:07:10.720
- It's an unknown.

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:15.290
And you're basically allowing
yourself to be an experiment.

00:07:15.290 --> 00:07:17.160
- We're coming in too fast.

00:07:17.160 --> 00:07:18.640
- Warning-- landing hazard.

00:07:18.640 --> 00:07:20.526
- [INAUDIBLE] just firing.

00:07:20.526 --> 00:07:23.358
- Hang on!

00:07:23.358 --> 00:07:23.858
- Ben?

00:07:23.858 --> 00:07:26.250
Can you hear me?

00:07:26.250 --> 00:07:28.960
- The question is, will
you be able to survive

00:07:28.960 --> 00:07:31.000
during this crucial
time of arrival?

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:33.410
- Ben, we're losing him.

00:07:33.410 --> 00:07:34.856
We're losing him!

00:07:37.416 --> 00:07:39.040
- These people are
putting their bodies

00:07:39.040 --> 00:07:43.240
at risk for us,
for the human race.

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:46.000
- When we get to Mars, we need
protection from radiation.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.050
- Unmanned aerial vehicle ready.

00:07:48.050 --> 00:07:50.290
- We'll use a fleet of
drones to find a lava

00:07:50.290 --> 00:07:52.060
tube with the conditions
we need to deploy

00:07:52.060 --> 00:07:53.267
a small domed habitat.

00:07:53.267 --> 00:07:54.850
- And that little
foothold will become

00:07:54.850 --> 00:07:56.990
humankind's first real
home beyond the gravity

00:07:56.990 --> 00:07:59.080
well, Olympus Town.

00:07:59.080 --> 00:08:01.270
- If I push this
modification any farther,

00:08:01.270 --> 00:08:03.860
we risk overloading the
entire electrical system.

00:08:03.860 --> 00:08:05.840
- We don't have
a choice, Robert.

00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:06.780
- Fire!

00:08:06.780 --> 00:08:09.130
- What did you do?

00:08:09.130 --> 00:08:10.070
[SCREAMS]

00:08:10.070 --> 00:08:12.870
- If the topography is
right and the ice is there,

00:08:12.870 --> 00:08:14.400
we can justify deployment.

00:08:14.400 --> 00:08:16.159
- I hope you're not
scared of the dark.

00:08:16.159 --> 00:08:21.910
[LAUGHS]

00:08:21.910 --> 00:08:25.580
- If there was water on
Mars, couldn't there possibly

00:08:25.580 --> 00:08:26.890
be life?

00:08:26.890 --> 00:08:30.055
- There's [INAUDIBLE].

00:08:30.055 --> 00:08:32.950
We're home.

00:08:32.950 --> 00:08:35.220
- Medical lab is
now operational.

00:08:35.220 --> 00:08:37.059
- The greenhouse is complete.

00:08:37.059 --> 00:08:40.059
- We at MMC feel that
we're ready to go faster.

00:08:40.059 --> 00:08:44.049
Phase two expansion will be
overseen by the very best.

00:08:44.049 --> 00:08:47.460
Our dream is now a reality.

00:08:47.460 --> 00:08:48.527
- They don't know Mars.

00:08:48.527 --> 00:08:50.110
You guys up for a
welcoming committee?

00:08:50.110 --> 00:08:51.997
Base commander, Hana Seung.

00:08:51.997 --> 00:08:53.830
- Within two months,
we'll have enough power

00:08:53.830 --> 00:08:56.404
to double the size and
capacity of your facilities.

00:08:56.404 --> 00:08:58.070
- It's a little too
ambitious right now.

00:08:58.070 --> 00:09:00.010
- You don't go to
Mars without ambition.

00:09:00.010 --> 00:09:02.093
- I don't think we're going
to get a chance to get

00:09:02.093 --> 00:09:05.230
that reactor back online.

00:09:05.230 --> 00:09:07.780
- If you got a dust storm
that lasted for a month,

00:09:07.780 --> 00:09:09.010
you'd be in big trouble.

00:09:09.010 --> 00:09:11.830
- This storm has been
raging for months.

00:09:11.830 --> 00:09:13.542
They call it a season.

00:09:13.542 --> 00:09:14.800
- I can't do my job.

00:09:14.800 --> 00:09:16.846
- Who is going to have
a real problem in space?

00:09:16.846 --> 00:09:18.220
Ultimately, there
are some people

00:09:18.220 --> 00:09:20.150
who are going to have
a really hard time.

00:09:20.150 --> 00:09:22.380
- The swarm is
getting to everyone.

00:09:22.380 --> 00:09:23.860
Are you missing home?

00:09:23.860 --> 00:09:24.590
- I'm OK.

00:09:24.590 --> 00:09:26.820
- He lives for his work.

00:09:26.820 --> 00:09:28.198
And he can't do it.

00:09:28.198 --> 00:09:28.876
Darling?

00:09:28.876 --> 00:09:30.785
- This is Paul Richardson.

00:09:30.785 --> 00:09:32.000
- What is he doing?

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.028
- Greenhouse air
lock compromised.

00:09:34.028 --> 00:09:34.694
- Seal the door!

00:09:41.470 --> 00:09:44.940
- As we buried our friends,
the fate of the mission

00:09:44.940 --> 00:09:46.980
was back on Earth.

00:09:46.980 --> 00:09:50.040
- If you send astronauts
to Mars and they die there,

00:09:50.040 --> 00:09:52.974
public opinion will prohibit
you from ever doing it again.

00:09:52.974 --> 00:09:55.140
- It's a time to be strong,
to make a statement that

00:09:55.140 --> 00:09:56.280
says we're here to stay.

00:09:56.280 --> 00:09:58.200
- Seven of the world's
most beloved scientists

00:09:58.200 --> 00:09:59.310
and astronauts are dead.

00:09:59.310 --> 00:10:01.268
You're not going to
influence my recommendation

00:10:01.268 --> 00:10:02.550
to the committee.

00:10:02.550 --> 00:10:07.990
- When we thought it could only
get darker, there was light.

00:10:07.990 --> 00:10:11.990
- We have been talking
about life on Mars forever.

00:10:11.990 --> 00:10:14.400
- Looks like
[INAUDIBLE] crystal.

00:10:14.400 --> 00:10:15.654
Javier and I found something.

00:10:15.654 --> 00:10:18.320
- Just think about what it would
mean if you found a single cell

00:10:18.320 --> 00:10:19.610
microorganism.

00:10:19.610 --> 00:10:26.170
- Today marks the end of an era
and the beginning of a new one.

00:10:26.170 --> 00:10:28.570
- It would be so exciting
to wake up in the morning

00:10:28.570 --> 00:10:30.760
and think that that's
what's happening.

00:10:30.760 --> 00:10:32.760
- There is life on Mars.

00:10:40.852 --> 00:10:42.290
- They're here.

00:10:42.290 --> 00:10:43.981
- Commander, incoming debris.

00:10:43.981 --> 00:10:44.480
Commander!

00:10:44.480 --> 00:10:44.944
Are you OK?

00:10:44.944 --> 00:10:45.443
- Get down!

00:10:50.007 --> 00:10:51.465
- I have big plans
for this planet.

00:10:51.465 --> 00:10:53.610
- We're not scientists,
for God's sake.

00:10:53.610 --> 00:10:54.580
We're miners.

00:10:54.580 --> 00:10:57.622
- With the advancement of
sciences comes industry.

00:10:57.622 --> 00:10:59.580
- We need to hook up your
water and your power.

00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:00.080
- Sorry?

00:11:00.080 --> 00:11:03.310
- [INAUDIBLE] says is becoming
irrelevant on your watch.

00:11:03.310 --> 00:11:06.730
- Mars, private enterprise--
yes, it's inevitable.

00:11:06.730 --> 00:11:09.640
- When we talk about
what we're doing on Mars,

00:11:09.640 --> 00:11:11.470
we're really talking
about what we

00:11:11.470 --> 00:11:13.750
think is OK to do
here on this planet.

00:11:13.750 --> 00:11:14.710
- What's that saying?

00:11:14.710 --> 00:11:15.670
Drill, baby, drill?

00:11:15.670 --> 00:11:18.510
- I myself have struck a
deal with Lukrum Industries.

00:11:18.510 --> 00:11:20.050
Give the miners what they want.

00:11:20.050 --> 00:11:21.340
- Yes, they're doing a job.

00:11:21.340 --> 00:11:24.100
But they also are creating
lives for themselves.

00:11:24.100 --> 00:11:26.560
- I came here for the adventure.

00:11:26.560 --> 00:11:27.340
- I'm pregnant.

00:11:27.340 --> 00:11:28.850
It's not like I planned it.

00:11:28.850 --> 00:11:29.350
- No.

00:11:29.350 --> 00:11:30.970
You just plan to leave.

00:11:30.970 --> 00:11:33.530
- If we go to Mars, you
don't want any surprises.

00:11:33.530 --> 00:11:35.170
- If this baby is born on Mars--

00:11:35.170 --> 00:11:36.810
- It could never leave here.

00:11:36.810 --> 00:11:38.380
- [INAUDIBLE]
talking [INAUDIBLE]..

00:11:38.380 --> 00:11:40.840
- Technology and workers
will be pushed faster

00:11:40.840 --> 00:11:41.981
than they should be pushed.

00:11:41.981 --> 00:11:42.730
- Let me help you.

00:11:42.730 --> 00:11:45.520
- And those errors have
disastrous consequences.

00:11:45.520 --> 00:11:47.540
[SCREAMING]

00:11:47.540 --> 00:11:50.540
- Coexistence may prove
just as challenging

00:11:50.540 --> 00:11:51.790
as it does on Earth.

00:11:51.790 --> 00:11:52.890
- Do you see something?

00:11:52.890 --> 00:11:54.480
- Only what we're looking for.

00:11:54.480 --> 00:11:56.646
- If you think I'm going
to let you and your company

00:11:56.646 --> 00:11:57.231
[INAUDIBLE]!

00:11:57.231 --> 00:11:58.897
- You're one crazy
bitch, you know that?

00:11:58.897 --> 00:12:00.210
[SMACK]

00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:02.055
- If there's a place
you've never been,

00:12:02.055 --> 00:12:04.180
there's a scientist who
wants to know what's there.

00:12:04.180 --> 00:12:06.520
- Companies want access
to new territory.

00:12:06.520 --> 00:12:09.190
At the same time, we
have a counter movement

00:12:09.190 --> 00:12:11.740
that says we're not going
down without a fight.

00:12:11.740 --> 00:12:13.570
- Mars is for those
willing to accept

00:12:13.570 --> 00:12:15.460
a much higher level of danger.

00:12:15.460 --> 00:12:17.934
- Solar flare.

00:12:17.934 --> 00:12:19.350
It's taken out our
electrical grid

00:12:19.350 --> 00:12:20.760
and our entire communications.

00:12:20.760 --> 00:12:22.830
She could freeze to
death before we find her.

00:12:25.950 --> 00:12:27.520
- We've disrupted
the environment,

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:30.900
creating new conditions
where diseases can spread.

00:12:30.900 --> 00:12:32.250
- [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:32.250 --> 00:12:33.210
- What do we got?

00:12:33.210 --> 00:12:35.430
- Something at the site
has been making them sick.

00:12:35.430 --> 00:12:36.750
- Stop the drilling.

00:12:36.750 --> 00:12:38.720
- When governments are
hiding an outbreak,

00:12:38.720 --> 00:12:40.470
that's when the virus
is actually winning.

00:12:40.470 --> 00:12:42.337
- I want to know the truth.

00:12:42.337 --> 00:12:42.920
- [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:42.920 --> 00:12:44.800
- You'd be walking
straight into the source.

00:12:44.800 --> 00:12:47.284
- I'm the only one who
knows this science.

00:12:47.284 --> 00:12:48.200
- She's not breathing!

00:12:48.200 --> 00:12:50.164
I need help!

00:12:50.164 --> 00:12:52.130
- He's dead.

00:12:52.130 --> 00:12:57.460
- It's my opinion that this
colony requires new leadership.

00:12:57.460 --> 00:12:59.230
- Lukrum colony disengaged.

00:12:59.230 --> 00:13:01.050
- Olympus Town--
pull the cord or not?

00:13:01.050 --> 00:13:04.450
- [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:04.450 --> 00:13:06.070
- People would lie,
cheat, and steal

00:13:06.070 --> 00:13:09.160
to make sure that the mission
was successful, even if that

00:13:09.160 --> 00:13:10.630
cost a lot of human lives.

00:13:10.630 --> 00:13:12.410
- I take orders
from my commander.

00:13:12.410 --> 00:13:14.650
- You do your job,
and I'll do mine.

00:13:14.650 --> 00:13:16.850
- They've taken advantage
of us at every turn.

00:13:16.850 --> 00:13:18.200
And you've let it happen.

00:13:18.200 --> 00:13:20.030
- Will we make mistakes on mars?

00:13:20.030 --> 00:13:20.530
Yes.

00:13:20.530 --> 00:13:21.720
[SCREAMING]

00:13:21.720 --> 00:13:23.680
- We have nothing
to show for it.

00:13:23.680 --> 00:13:27.180
- You see something that
has unimaginable wealth.

00:13:27.180 --> 00:13:28.340
And you want to go get it.

00:13:28.340 --> 00:13:30.190
