00:15:54.689 --> 00:15:56.230
STEPHEN PETRANEK:
Well, I have a mic.

00:15:56.230 --> 00:15:58.420
Good.

00:15:58.420 --> 00:15:59.830
Well, it was a big shock.

00:15:59.830 --> 00:16:04.690
I've been a science
journalist my whole life.

00:16:04.690 --> 00:16:08.410
And I've never been
kind of buffered up

00:16:08.410 --> 00:16:11.290
against the Hollywood syndrome.

00:16:11.290 --> 00:16:14.770
So when we first got involved
in this project and the book

00:16:14.770 --> 00:16:18.144
was first optioned
by RadicalMedia,

00:16:18.144 --> 00:16:19.810
there were all kinds
of twists and turns

00:16:19.810 --> 00:16:23.020
that were kind of crazy,
like getting SpaceX

00:16:23.020 --> 00:16:26.710
to cooperate with
us, which was a very

00:16:26.710 --> 00:16:29.980
difficult problem initially.

00:16:29.980 --> 00:16:34.870
And then, seeing how this
concept of storytelling

00:16:34.870 --> 00:16:39.310
was far more important to
anyone on the West Coast

00:16:39.310 --> 00:16:42.190
than the facts were to anyone
on the East Coast, where I was.

00:16:42.190 --> 00:16:45.350
So there was kind of this
thing going on between us.

00:16:45.350 --> 00:16:51.430
And my role quickly became
not just explaining,

00:16:51.430 --> 00:16:55.420
as was Bobby's role,
initially, in the show,

00:16:55.420 --> 00:16:58.090
not just explaining
to the filmmaking

00:16:58.090 --> 00:17:00.440
people and the
actors and so forth

00:17:00.440 --> 00:17:02.020
what the real facts
were about being

00:17:02.020 --> 00:17:04.089
on Mars and the kinds of
scenarios you could have

00:17:04.089 --> 00:17:05.005
and you couldn't have.

00:17:05.005 --> 00:17:07.839
For example, I will
never forget a phone call

00:17:07.839 --> 00:17:11.859
from the director
in the first season.

00:17:11.859 --> 00:17:14.829
And we were talking about
actually leaving Earth

00:17:14.829 --> 00:17:16.180
and going to Mars and the trip.

00:17:16.180 --> 00:17:18.710
And they said, OK,
somebody's gotta die on this.

00:17:18.710 --> 00:17:20.799
How are they going to die?

00:17:20.799 --> 00:17:22.340
So I gave them,
like, five scenarios.

00:17:22.340 --> 00:17:26.020
And my favorite scenario
was that a small meteoroid

00:17:26.020 --> 00:17:28.150
would pass through the rocket.

00:17:28.150 --> 00:17:29.740
And they said no,
we don't like that.

00:17:29.740 --> 00:17:31.952
And then I gave them a
couple other scenarios.

00:17:31.952 --> 00:17:32.910
No, we don't like that.

00:17:32.910 --> 00:17:33.993
And I gave them a couple--

00:17:33.993 --> 00:17:35.150
no, I don't like that.

00:17:35.150 --> 00:17:38.830
And it was, like, well,
wait a minute, you know?

00:17:38.830 --> 00:17:40.720
What kind of
scenario do you want?

00:17:40.720 --> 00:17:42.400
And they would
give me one, and I

00:17:42.400 --> 00:17:46.650
would say that isn't
physically possible in space.

00:17:46.650 --> 00:17:53.800
So initially, there was a lot
of conflict and buffering,

00:17:53.800 --> 00:17:55.300
trying to come up--

00:17:55.300 --> 00:17:58.540
trying to get the people who
wanted to do the storytelling

00:17:58.540 --> 00:18:03.544
and were very good at it to
adapt to the physical realities

00:18:03.544 --> 00:18:04.210
of the universe.

00:18:04.210 --> 00:18:06.550
[LAUGHTER]

00:18:06.550 --> 00:18:08.200
But in the end, it
worked out great.

00:18:08.200 --> 00:18:10.930
And one of the things
that really surprised me

00:18:10.930 --> 00:18:15.370
was that both the
actors and the directors

00:18:15.370 --> 00:18:17.410
were really eager to learn.

00:18:17.410 --> 00:18:20.829
Like, when I first met the
initial group of actors,

00:18:20.829 --> 00:18:22.620
every single one of
them had read the book.

00:18:22.620 --> 00:18:25.000
Some of them had read the
book two or three times.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:26.920
And the book served
as kind of a primer,

00:18:26.920 --> 00:18:29.530
because it kind of laid
out all the facts of what

00:18:29.530 --> 00:18:32.290
it would be like on Mars, what
it would be like getting there.

00:18:32.290 --> 00:18:35.740
What if, you know, it's
very science-based and very

00:18:35.740 --> 00:18:36.760
fact-based.

00:18:36.760 --> 00:18:41.630
And they really absorbed that
and wanted to learn that.

00:18:41.630 --> 00:18:45.300
So it's been a lot of fun.

00:18:45.300 --> 00:18:47.710
And I've learned an awful lot.

00:18:47.710 --> 00:18:51.100
You know, I thought, as a
journalist and as a writer

00:18:51.100 --> 00:18:52.300
and as an editor--

00:18:52.300 --> 00:18:56.410
and you know, I used to be
kind of a writer's editor

00:18:56.410 --> 00:18:58.690
who worked with really
long form kind of stories

00:18:58.690 --> 00:19:00.190
that you would--
the kind of stories

00:19:00.190 --> 00:19:02.740
you would see in "The New
Yorker" or "The New York Times

00:19:02.740 --> 00:19:04.510
Sunday Magazine."

00:19:04.510 --> 00:19:07.450
I thought I knew
everything that I was ever

00:19:07.450 --> 00:19:09.290
going to need to know
about storytelling.

00:19:09.290 --> 00:19:14.970
And this new dimension, which is
visual, taught me an awful lot.

00:19:14.970 --> 00:19:16.700
And it taught me an
awful lot about scene

00:19:16.700 --> 00:19:20.390
setting in words, as
well as in visuals

00:19:20.390 --> 00:19:22.340
and carrying
through a storyline.

00:19:22.340 --> 00:19:26.960
So I'm very grateful for
the whole experience.

00:19:26.960 --> 00:19:28.550
BOBBY BRAUN: Thank you.

00:19:28.550 --> 00:19:29.210
Thanks.

00:19:29.210 --> 00:19:34.365
Antonia, first of all, welcome
back to Boulder, your hometown.

00:19:34.365 --> 00:19:35.615
ANTONIA JUHASZ: I'm from here.

00:19:35.615 --> 00:19:36.410
It's nice to be back.

00:19:36.410 --> 00:19:36.830
BOBBY BRAUN: That's great.

00:19:36.830 --> 00:19:38.090
ANTONIA JUHASZ: Yeah.

00:19:38.090 --> 00:19:40.550
BOBBY BRAUN: You play a
