00:19:55.280 --> 00:19:58.610
and challenges in that vein.

00:19:58.610 --> 00:20:02.900
Can you talk a little
bit more about how

00:20:02.900 --> 00:20:06.920
you view what we're doing
today, presently, to the Earth

00:20:06.920 --> 00:20:08.510
and on the Earth--

00:20:08.510 --> 00:20:12.645
how you view that playing
out in the future on Mars?

00:20:12.645 --> 00:20:13.520
ANTONIA JUHASZ: Yeah.

00:20:13.520 --> 00:20:14.390
It is great to be home.

00:20:14.390 --> 00:20:15.440
I live in San Francisco now.

00:20:15.440 --> 00:20:16.250
But I grew up in Boulder.

00:20:16.250 --> 00:20:17.960
So it's really great
to be back here

00:20:17.960 --> 00:20:20.450
and see the brand new campus
and thanks for all of you

00:20:20.450 --> 00:20:21.600
for being here.

00:20:21.600 --> 00:20:24.455
So as you saw in the previews,
what's really exciting--

00:20:24.455 --> 00:20:27.080
one of the things that's really
exciting about the show is I do

00:20:27.080 --> 00:20:30.560
think this model is
entirely unique and a just

00:20:30.560 --> 00:20:33.110
revolutionary way of
storytelling-- which

00:20:33.110 --> 00:20:35.780
is the hybrid of the
documentary and the drama.

00:20:35.780 --> 00:20:37.640
So they're interlaced,
as you saw.

00:20:37.640 --> 00:20:40.560
You've got the dramatic
series in the future on Mars.

00:20:40.560 --> 00:20:42.760
And then you have
the documentary.

00:20:42.760 --> 00:20:44.510
And you go back and
forth between the two,

00:20:44.510 --> 00:20:46.960
and both sets become
characters, in a way.

00:20:46.960 --> 00:20:49.782
You want to know, I
think, not only what's

00:20:49.782 --> 00:20:51.740
going to happen to the
characters in the drama,

00:20:51.740 --> 00:20:53.930
but what the next big
thinker is going to say.

00:20:53.930 --> 00:20:55.670
Because you also become
invested in them,

00:20:55.670 --> 00:20:57.800
because they're carried
through this storyline,

00:20:57.800 --> 00:20:59.940
the documentary
storyline, as well.

00:20:59.940 --> 00:21:01.790
But in the first
season, the documentary

00:21:01.790 --> 00:21:04.880
is basically about the
science of getting to Mars.

00:21:04.880 --> 00:21:07.370
In the second season,
the documentary

00:21:07.370 --> 00:21:13.070
is really about what are
the unforeseen consequences

00:21:13.070 --> 00:21:15.470
that we've treated as
unforeseen consequences

00:21:15.470 --> 00:21:20.030
on Earth that have led us to
a devastation of our ability

00:21:20.030 --> 00:21:21.830
to cohabitate with this planet?

00:21:21.830 --> 00:21:25.280
And will we follow
those same failures

00:21:25.280 --> 00:21:26.450
as we go to the next planet?

00:21:26.450 --> 00:21:29.030
And trying to learn
those lessons--

00:21:29.030 --> 00:21:31.250
and that's basically,
from my perspective,

00:21:31.250 --> 00:21:34.100
or at least my role in the
documentary, my role is about--

00:21:34.100 --> 00:21:39.170
is looking at the failure of
resource extraction on Earth

00:21:39.170 --> 00:21:42.410
and will the failure of
resource extraction on Earth

00:21:42.410 --> 00:21:45.380
be carried forward?

00:21:45.380 --> 00:21:47.840
And the failure of resource
extraction on Earth

00:21:47.840 --> 00:21:49.842
is really well-embodied
in oil extraction.

00:21:49.842 --> 00:21:51.800
And so that's sort of
the tool that's followed.

00:21:51.800 --> 00:21:54.300
In season two, as
you saw, Greenpeace

00:21:54.300 --> 00:21:56.960
is followed as they
go head to head

00:21:56.960 --> 00:22:00.920
with oil drilling in the
Arctic, with the outcome of oil

00:22:00.920 --> 00:22:04.220
drilling in the Yamal
Peninsula of the Russian Arctic

00:22:04.220 --> 00:22:09.140
and in the drilling platform
in the Norwegian Arctic.

00:22:09.140 --> 00:22:15.770
And I think what is really some
of the crux of the storyline

00:22:15.770 --> 00:22:18.680
and how I have
summarized the two

00:22:18.680 --> 00:22:22.970
seasons from my own perspective
is the first season is looking

00:22:22.970 --> 00:22:26.390
at will Mars kill the
humans that go there,

00:22:26.390 --> 00:22:30.050
and the second season is
will the humans kill Mars.

00:22:30.050 --> 00:22:34.670
And that is looking at
what's going to happen when

00:22:34.670 --> 00:22:38.960
and if this major
industry comes.

00:22:38.960 --> 00:22:44.900
And the depiction of the
industry in Lukrum Industries

00:22:44.900 --> 00:22:48.470
is really incredibly spot
on-- in the way it's written,

00:22:48.470 --> 00:22:54.020
in the portrayal of the actors,
in the difficulties they face

00:22:54.020 --> 00:22:56.390
and the decision to--

00:22:56.390 --> 00:23:01.760
as Jeff, who's the actor
in the clip, says--

00:23:01.760 --> 00:23:03.815
"drill, baby, drill",
quoting Sarah Palin.

00:23:07.820 --> 00:23:10.410
And I think that the
lessons are really

00:23:10.410 --> 00:23:12.930
well-embodied in
both sets of stories.

00:23:12.930 --> 00:23:14.940
One of the critical
issues that's

00:23:14.940 --> 00:23:18.000
raised, is there life on Mars--

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:21.200
one of the big challenges that
happens with oil drilling,

00:23:21.200 --> 00:23:23.364
and what one sees over
and over and over again

00:23:23.364 --> 00:23:25.530
with oil drilling, the
history of the last 150 years

00:23:25.530 --> 00:23:29.760
of oil drilling, is the
drilling goes first and only

00:23:29.760 --> 00:23:32.430
afterwards do we
then learn, oh, wait.

00:23:32.430 --> 00:23:34.950
There was this really
critical natural resource.

00:23:34.950 --> 00:23:37.800
There was this group of
people who lived here.

00:23:37.800 --> 00:23:40.230
There are all sorts of
consequences that only get

00:23:40.230 --> 00:23:42.690
thought of as an afterthought.

00:23:42.690 --> 00:23:46.470
And one of the best examples
of that in Arctic drilling,

00:23:46.470 --> 00:23:49.890
which I think is a good parallel
to what could happen on Mars,

00:23:49.890 --> 00:23:51.990
is something that seems
really inconsequential,

00:23:51.990 --> 00:23:53.130
and that's phytoplankton.

00:23:53.130 --> 00:23:55.050
It just looks like a seaweed.

00:23:55.050 --> 00:23:56.820
But it turns out
that phytoplankton,

00:23:56.820 --> 00:23:57.960
if you destroy it--

00:23:57.960 --> 00:24:01.240
it provides 50% of the oxygen
we need to live on the planet.

00:24:01.240 --> 00:24:05.010
So treating it as a sort
of inconsequential thing

00:24:05.010 --> 00:24:07.980
is one of the reasons why we're
facing the problem that we're

00:24:07.980 --> 00:24:09.340
