STEPHEN PETRANEK: Vice
presidents at Fox.

00:30:42.400 --> 00:30:43.275
ANTONIA JUHASZ: Yeah.

00:30:43.275 --> 00:30:45.980
[LAUGHTER]

00:30:45.980 --> 00:30:48.380
BOBBY BRAUN: There's a
question in the middle there?

00:30:48.380 --> 00:30:50.920
AUDIENCE: So we've been
imagining Mars colonization

00:30:50.920 --> 00:30:52.960
for years and years and years.

00:30:52.960 --> 00:30:57.220
Thinking about today, what
things, challenges had we

00:30:57.220 --> 00:30:59.870
anticipated before that we're
now better able to deal with?

00:30:59.870 --> 00:31:02.920
And what new challenges
have we discovered that we

00:31:02.920 --> 00:31:05.590
didn't foresee back then?

00:31:05.590 --> 00:31:07.570
STEPHEN PETRANEK:
That's probably for you.

00:31:07.570 --> 00:31:08.819
BOBBY BRAUN: Well, I'll start.

00:31:08.819 --> 00:31:10.990
But you can always add in.

00:31:10.990 --> 00:31:17.170
So I would argue that we've made
great progress in determining

00:31:17.170 --> 00:31:20.270
how to land big things on Mars.

00:31:20.270 --> 00:31:25.250
So this is an area that I've
worked in most of my career.

00:31:25.250 --> 00:31:28.990
And if you had asked
me 10 years ago

00:31:28.990 --> 00:31:31.795
how we were going to land humans
on Mars, I would have said,

00:31:31.795 --> 00:31:34.720
you know, I don't know.

00:31:34.720 --> 00:31:36.910
There were a lot of ideas
out there 10 years ago

00:31:36.910 --> 00:31:37.990
or even 20 years ago.

00:31:37.990 --> 00:31:40.630
There were a lot
of cartoon drawings

00:31:40.630 --> 00:31:43.400
that showed how
one might do that.

00:31:43.400 --> 00:31:47.080
But none of that
technology had been proven.

00:31:47.080 --> 00:31:50.650
And recently, actually
here on the Earth,

00:31:50.650 --> 00:31:54.320
we've done a lot to
prove those technologies.

00:31:54.320 --> 00:31:58.450
So one example
would be when SpaceX

00:31:58.450 --> 00:32:01.060
returns these first stage
boosters that they've

00:32:01.060 --> 00:32:05.560
done successfully over
30 times now, way up high

00:32:05.560 --> 00:32:08.500
in the atmosphere when they're
bringing that booster back,

00:32:08.500 --> 00:32:11.400
they call out something
called an entry burn.

00:32:11.400 --> 00:32:15.070
And that burn takes
place supersonically

00:32:15.070 --> 00:32:17.290
in Mars-relevant conditions.

00:32:17.290 --> 00:32:18.670
Because you're up
so high, you're

00:32:18.670 --> 00:32:23.350
up around 100,000 feet or higher
when that burn takes place.

00:32:23.350 --> 00:32:25.540
And what they're
doing is they're

00:32:25.540 --> 00:32:30.890
firing their jets in opposite to
the direction of the velocity.

00:32:30.890 --> 00:32:33.162
So opposing free stream.

00:32:33.162 --> 00:32:34.870
And that's something
that actually people

00:32:34.870 --> 00:32:36.070
have talked about a lot.

00:32:36.070 --> 00:32:39.160
But until SpaceX had
a need to do that,

00:32:39.160 --> 00:32:42.130
no one had ever done that
in Mars-relevant conditions.

00:32:42.130 --> 00:32:43.660
And as I've said,
they've done it--

00:32:43.660 --> 00:32:45.910
for a big piece of
hardware, they've

00:32:45.910 --> 00:32:48.614
done it 30 times or
more successfully.

00:32:48.614 --> 00:32:50.530
You don't see that because
it happens so high.

00:32:50.530 --> 00:32:54.430
You see the booster coming
down right on the drone ship.

00:32:54.430 --> 00:32:56.740
And that's exciting, too.

00:32:56.740 --> 00:32:59.830
But for those of us that
are focused on Mars,

00:32:59.830 --> 00:33:04.570
we care about what happened at
40 kilometers or so altitude.

00:33:04.570 --> 00:33:06.620
Also, through the
robotic program--

00:33:06.620 --> 00:33:11.890
I mean, I started my career
by landing Mars Pathfinder

00:33:11.890 --> 00:33:13.000
on the surface.

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:15.310
It landed a little rover
called Sojourner that

00:33:15.310 --> 00:33:17.610
was about the size of a baby.

00:33:17.610 --> 00:33:20.050
It was 11 kilograms in mass.

00:33:20.050 --> 00:33:22.960
And you know, Mars
Science Laboratory is

00:33:22.960 --> 00:33:25.150
the size of a small car, right?

00:33:25.150 --> 00:33:28.460
It's a nuclear powered
car with a laser on it.

00:33:28.460 --> 00:33:29.330
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:29.330 --> 00:33:29.890
Right?

00:33:29.890 --> 00:33:32.390
That we landed in 2012--

00:33:32.390 --> 00:33:35.000
and by the way, in
2020, we're going

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:37.350
to land much more accurately.

00:33:37.350 --> 00:33:40.130
We're going to land
basically in a football field

00:33:40.130 --> 00:33:44.360
instead of in a 20
kilometer safe zone.

00:33:44.360 --> 00:33:48.470
So that kind of
accuracy is required

00:33:48.470 --> 00:33:50.750
to build up a base camp, right?

00:33:50.750 --> 00:33:53.840
In the series, you see that
there have been many landings.

00:33:53.840 --> 00:33:55.880
And in order to build
up this base camp

00:33:55.880 --> 00:33:59.300
those many landings have to
happen in close proximity

00:33:59.300 --> 00:34:02.630
to each other to get all
that hardware together.

00:34:02.630 --> 00:34:05.390
And that's a technology
that we're improving.

00:34:05.390 --> 00:34:10.580
I think our ability to
keep people alive, frankly,

00:34:10.580 --> 00:34:14.030
and to keep them safe so that
they can live, play, and work

00:34:14.030 --> 00:34:17.270
in space, both in the
microgravity environment

00:34:17.270 --> 00:34:19.429
of space and on
another planet, has

00:34:19.429 --> 00:34:21.290
been greatly advanced
by what we're

00:34:21.290 --> 00:34:24.230
doing on the International
Space Station today.

00:34:24.230 --> 00:34:26.489
Leonard mentioned the three
astronauts that just went.

00:34:26.489 --> 00:34:29.300
But they joined three others
that are already there.

00:34:29.300 --> 00:34:35.060
And we've had people
from our planet in space

00:34:35.060 --> 00:34:38.120
continuously since 2001.

00:34:38.120 --> 00:34:38.929
Think about that.

00:34:38.929 --> 00:34:43.880
Not the same people,
but I mean, that's

00:34:43.880 --> 00:34:46.880
a remarkable achievement
for our planet.

00:34:46.880 --> 00:34:48.400
And it's not just
Americans, right?

00:34:48.400 --> 00:34:52.940
There are international
astronauts included in that.

00:34:52.940 --> 00:34:55.489
And to think that we've
lived off of our world

00:34:55.489 --> 00:34:58.610
continuously, some
small subset of us

00:34:58.610 --> 00:35:04.190
have done so continuously
and safely since 2001,

00:35:04.190 --> 00:35:07.160
that tells you something about
the reliability of the system

00:35:07.160 --> 00:35:10.520
the crew systems needed
to keep people safe,

00:35:10.520 --> 00:35:13.700
about food processing, about
water processing, radiation

00:35:13.700 --> 00:35:14.810
shielding.

00:35:14.810 --> 00:35:17.450
All of the kinds of
technologies that you see

00:35:17.450 --> 00:35:21.286
played out in this series,
they're happening today.

00:35:21.286 --> 00:35:23.035
And then the last piece
that I'll mention,

00:35:23.035 --> 00:35:24.620
and I'll see if you
want to add to that--

00:35:24.620 --> 00:35:25.010
STEPHEN PETRANEK: Correct.

00:35:25.010 --> 00:35:26.390
BOBBY BRAUN: --is really--

00:35:26.390 --> 00:35:30.290
correct-- is just the
advancement of industry,

00:35:30.290 --> 00:35:32.240
frankly, in this country.

00:35:32.240 --> 00:35:34.490
It's one thing
for our government

00:35:34.490 --> 00:35:37.570
to be talking about sending
humans back to the moon.

00:35:37.570 --> 00:35:42.320
It's a great, exciting
thing to repeat

00:35:42.320 --> 00:35:46.260
something like the Apollo
missions from the 1960s.

00:35:46.260 --> 00:35:50.030
It would be a fantastic
achievement for our country.

00:35:50.030 --> 00:35:53.270
But what really impresses
me and gets me going,

00:35:53.270 --> 00:35:57.260
gets my juices going, is
the industry capabilities

00:35:57.260 --> 00:36:00.290
in this country at
places like SpaceX,

00:36:00.290 --> 00:36:04.580
or you know, right here in
Colorado at Lockheed Martin,

00:36:04.580 --> 00:36:09.500
or what's going on with Blue
Origin or Virgin Galactic,

00:36:09.500 --> 00:36:12.800
all of these companies
that are on their own

00:36:12.800 --> 00:36:15.590
contributing to
the space economy.

00:36:15.590 --> 00:36:19.790
Planet Labs, that is
basically building

00:36:19.790 --> 00:36:23.950
almost a real-time
Google Earth, right?

00:36:23.950 --> 00:36:27.110
You know, it's remarkable
what's happening in space today.

00:36:27.110 --> 00:36:32.240
And I think that capability is
required for us to efficiently

00:36:32.240 --> 00:36:36.405
and cost effectively go to Mars.

00:36:36.405 --> 00:36:38.780
STEPHEN PETRANEK: I think from
a technical point of view,

00:36:38.780 --> 00:36:41.120
one of the most interesting
things about going to Mars

00:36:41.120 --> 00:36:44.660
is that most of the technology
that you needed to do this

00:36:44.660 --> 00:36:47.120
has been available
for at least 30 years.

00:36:47.120 --> 00:36:51.350
I'd like to say 40 years,
but probably 30 years.

00:36:51.350 --> 00:36:54.230
There's a device on the
new Curiosity rover that's

00:36:54.230 --> 00:36:57.980
going up in 2020 called MOXIE
that will split the carbon

00:36:57.980 --> 00:37:01.400
atom off the CO2
atmosphere of Mars

00:37:01.400 --> 00:37:07.190
and create enough oxygen for
one human being to breathe

00:37:07.190 --> 00:37:08.630
consistently, for example.

00:37:08.630 --> 00:37:11.570
That machine is
supposed to be scaled,

00:37:11.570 --> 00:37:14.180
is designed to be scaled
up by a factor of 100.

00:37:14.180 --> 00:37:16.790
I think NASA originally
wanted that machine

00:37:16.790 --> 00:37:20.120
so that they could have
an oxidizer on Mars

00:37:20.120 --> 00:37:23.889
to make rocket fuel for a
return trip in the future.

00:37:23.889 --> 00:37:25.430
But in fact, that
machine is probably

00:37:25.430 --> 00:37:27.380
going to turn out to
be the machine that

00:37:27.380 --> 00:37:30.459
makes the oxygen that people
need to breathe on Mars.

00:37:30.459 --> 00:37:32.000
I'm not quite sure
what they're going

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:36.440
to use for the rest of the
inert gas, the other 78%.

00:37:36.440 --> 00:37:38.610
That is still a
technical problem.

00:37:38.610 --> 00:37:41.110
But what's amazing
is that all this

00:37:41.110 --> 00:37:46.040
stuff-- you know, we made this
decision to stay in Earth orbit

00:37:46.040 --> 00:37:49.377
a long, long time ago, as
the Apollo program was coming

00:37:49.377 --> 00:37:51.710
to an end and we decided to
build a space shuttle, which

00:37:51.710 --> 00:37:53.360
is supposed to be
cheap and reusable

00:37:53.360 --> 00:37:57.770
and turned out to cost about
over a billion for each flight.

00:37:57.770 --> 00:38:00.470
And we have not
kind of reached out

00:38:00.470 --> 00:38:03.480
and extended what
we're capable of doing.

00:38:03.480 --> 00:38:05.210
We haven't gone back
to the moon, which I

00:38:05.210 --> 00:38:06.501
think would be kind of a waste.

00:38:06.501 --> 00:38:09.680
But we haven't taken
a bold step like we

00:38:09.680 --> 00:38:12.770
did in the Apollo
program and decided

00:38:12.770 --> 00:38:14.780
to let's just go to Mars.

00:38:14.780 --> 00:38:16.400
And yet we've had
this capability

00:38:16.400 --> 00:38:18.470
to do this for so long.

00:38:18.470 --> 00:38:21.080
And to touch on one other thing
that both Leonard and Bobby

00:38:21.080 --> 00:38:22.340
have touched on.

00:38:22.340 --> 00:38:24.260
Space is the next big business.

00:38:24.260 --> 00:38:27.950
It isn't an accident that you
see all these things happening

00:38:27.950 --> 00:38:29.640
in the last week or so.

00:38:29.640 --> 00:38:32.580
The Russians have
committed to going to Mars

00:38:32.580 --> 00:38:33.930
and putting a human on Mars.

00:38:33.930 --> 00:38:36.990
The Chinese have committed
to putting a human on Mars.

00:38:36.990 --> 00:38:38.400
Both the Russians
and the Chinese

00:38:38.400 --> 00:38:42.210
have committed to put
humans on the moon again.

00:38:42.210 --> 00:38:45.750
NASA has committed just recently
to putting humans on the moon

00:38:45.750 --> 00:38:47.220
again.

00:38:47.220 --> 00:38:51.060
And yet, as Bobby says, there
are all these private companies

00:38:51.060 --> 00:38:52.800
that could actually
do it maybe even

00:38:52.800 --> 00:38:54.930
before any of these
governments could do it,

00:38:54.930 --> 00:38:58.050
companies like SpaceX, which
actually intend to do it

00:38:58.050 --> 00:39:00.040
before a government does it.

00:39:00.040 --> 00:39:02.460
This is the next big business.

00:39:02.460 --> 00:39:07.680
Lassoing the SLS launch
system and the Orion capsule

00:39:07.680 --> 00:39:10.530
that NASA has built, one
of the original things

00:39:10.530 --> 00:39:12.270
they wanted to do
with that literally

00:39:12.270 --> 00:39:15.300
was to go out and find a
near-Earth asteroid and lasso

00:39:15.300 --> 00:39:18.420
it and bring it back and put
it in orbit around the moon

00:39:18.420 --> 00:39:21.780
so that commercial companies
could practice mining it.

00:39:21.780 --> 00:39:22.770
That's real!

00:39:22.770 --> 00:39:24.960
That's real technology
that we have now

00:39:24.960 --> 00:39:27.600
that we're capable of doing.

00:39:27.600 --> 00:39:31.920
It's just going to be mind
blowing how this stuff expands.

00:39:31.920 --> 00:39:36.150
And it's expanding a lot because
of the commercial aspects

00:39:36.150 --> 00:39:36.900
of space.

00:39:36.900 --> 00:39:39.519
It's really going to
be a big business.

00:39:39.519 --> 00:39:42.060
ANTONIA JUHASZ: I think that's
the perfect place to chime in.

00:39:42.060 --> 00:39:45.660
I think that what is
happening very rapidly

00:39:45.660 --> 00:39:51.210
is the movement towards securing
ownership of resources, who's

00:39:51.210 --> 00:39:52.800
going to own the resources.

00:39:52.800 --> 00:39:56.130
And the only existing
international architecture

00:39:56.130 --> 00:39:58.572
was the moon treaty--

00:39:58.572 --> 00:40:00.030
STEPHEN PETRANEK:
'67 space treaty.

00:40:00.030 --> 00:40:02.490
ANTONIA JUHASZ: Outer
space 1967 treaty.

00:40:02.490 --> 00:40:05.016
And the goal was to not
have a militarized space.

00:40:05.016 --> 00:40:06.390
That was the goal
of that treaty.

00:40:06.390 --> 00:40:07.860
It was a peace treaty.

00:40:07.860 --> 00:40:10.080
Now it's being written,
our attempts-- there's

00:40:10.080 --> 00:40:11.910
already national
legislation that's

00:40:11.910 --> 00:40:13.980
happened in the United
States and other attempts

00:40:13.980 --> 00:40:17.340
that are being written
to define ownership

00:40:17.340 --> 00:40:19.740
of what you would mine
in space, who owns it,

00:40:19.740 --> 00:40:21.109
who gets to profit from it.

00:40:21.109 --> 00:40:22.650
And that's all being
driven right now

00:40:22.650 --> 00:40:25.320
by private companies, period.

00:40:25.320 --> 00:40:27.630
And that is a
similar model, which

00:40:27.630 --> 00:40:31.110
is will the private companies
gain ownership of asteroids

00:40:31.110 --> 00:40:33.870
and the rights to mine
asteroids and other planets

00:40:33.870 --> 00:40:36.060
and what they get there
and how they do it?

00:40:36.060 --> 00:40:40.230
And will a regulatory regime
only catch up afterwards,

00:40:40.230 --> 00:40:41.530
after it's happening?

00:40:41.530 --> 00:40:44.100
And if that happens, are
the unintended consequences

00:40:44.100 --> 00:40:47.490
of mining asteroids
being thought

00:40:47.490 --> 00:40:50.460
through by the people who are
intending to do the mining?

00:40:50.460 --> 00:40:52.350
Or will that be an afterthought?

00:40:52.350 --> 00:40:55.900
So Osiris-REx,
one of its goals--

00:40:55.900 --> 00:40:59.340
this is the mission that
Leonard just mentioned--

00:40:59.340 --> 00:41:02.077
that just yesterday
successfully--

00:41:02.077 --> 00:41:03.660
STEPHEN PETRANEK:
Got to [INAUDIBLE]..

00:41:03.660 --> 00:41:04.530
It does--

00:41:04.530 --> 00:41:05.070
ANTONIA JUHASZ: Got there.

00:41:05.070 --> 00:41:06.300
STEPHEN PETRANEK:
--recovery [? route. ?]

00:41:06.300 --> 00:41:07.758
ANTONIA JUHASZ:
One of its goals is

00:41:07.758 --> 00:41:10.740
to determine the viability
of asteroid mining.

00:41:10.740 --> 00:41:12.210
That's one of the intentions.

00:41:12.210 --> 00:41:13.890
And so for someone
like me, who has

00:41:13.890 --> 00:41:20.940
spent her career looking at
this sort of the industry

00:41:20.940 --> 00:41:22.890
goes forward and sort
of regulation's attempt

00:41:22.890 --> 00:41:26.040
to follow afterwards, and what
the consequences of those are,

00:41:26.040 --> 00:41:28.500
thinking about it now for me
in this entirely new realm

00:41:28.500 --> 00:41:31.270
which is all of space.

00:41:31.270 --> 00:41:34.620
And what the unintended
consequences could be

00:41:34.620 --> 00:41:36.030
is truly profound.

00:41:36.030 --> 00:41:39.270
And trying to
encourage the public

00:41:39.270 --> 00:41:43.230
to participate in this
process as much as industry

00:41:43.230 --> 00:41:48.562
is before the cat gets much
further out of the bag.

00:41:48.562 --> 00:41:50.270
LEONARD DAVID: There's
some kind of line,

00:41:50.270 --> 00:41:52.500
and I don't think
I came up with it.

00:41:52.500 --> 00:41:54.870
I stole it from
somebody, probably.

00:41:54.870 --> 00:42:00.360
But you do the peaceful
uses of outer space.

00:42:00.360 --> 00:42:04.630
And then somebody
says, the useful--

00:42:04.630 --> 00:42:05.360
how does this go?

00:42:05.360 --> 00:42:06.930
Now I can't remember
what I'm talking about.

00:42:06.930 --> 00:42:07.620
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:07.620 --> 00:42:08.205
OK.

00:42:08.205 --> 00:42:09.887
Useful pieces of outer space.

00:42:09.887 --> 00:42:10.762
ANTONIA JUHASZ: Yeah.

00:42:10.762 --> 00:42:11.400
That works.

00:42:11.400 --> 00:42:14.040
LEONARD DAVID: And
that's interesting.

00:42:14.040 --> 00:42:16.030
One little, quick short story.

00:42:16.030 --> 00:42:17.340
I used to go--

00:42:17.340 --> 00:42:18.840
every time there
was a Mars mission,

00:42:18.840 --> 00:42:23.820
I'd go to JPL ahead of time,
go talk to all the engineers.

00:42:23.820 --> 00:42:28.780
And one time I went in there,
and this was on Pathfinder.

00:42:28.780 --> 00:42:35.510
The head guy goes and puts me in
his office and shuts the door.

00:42:35.510 --> 00:42:40.010
And he says, if this fails, how
will you guys report on this?

00:42:40.010 --> 00:42:42.730
And I said, well, how is
this really going to work?

00:42:42.730 --> 00:42:45.170
He said, we're using airbags--

00:42:45.170 --> 00:42:45.900
airbags.

00:42:45.900 --> 00:42:48.200
OK, let's see how that one goes.

00:42:48.200 --> 00:42:50.660
But that mission
was the first time

00:42:50.660 --> 00:42:52.700
I ever heard of
co-location, which

00:42:52.700 --> 00:42:54.890
is what you folks do here.

00:42:54.890 --> 00:42:56.540
And that was why it succeeded.

00:42:56.540 --> 00:43:00.680
They had people co-located
in the same buildings

00:43:00.680 --> 00:43:02.790
to talk to each other.

00:43:02.790 --> 00:43:07.210
People that were working
on a parachute for a month

00:43:07.210 --> 00:43:10.650
would all of a sudden be going
over to another part of--

00:43:10.650 --> 00:43:12.290
the wheels of the rover.

00:43:12.290 --> 00:43:17.360
Each person learned more
about their spacecraft.

00:43:17.360 --> 00:43:18.800
But that was called co-location.

00:43:18.800 --> 00:43:21.140
And then I went back
a couple years ago,

00:43:21.140 --> 00:43:23.510
before Curiosity landed.

00:43:23.510 --> 00:43:25.290
How are you going to land that?

00:43:25.290 --> 00:43:26.900
Oh, a sky crane--

00:43:26.900 --> 00:43:29.390
it'll be dropped
down on a tether.

00:43:29.390 --> 00:43:30.950
And you're going--

00:43:30.950 --> 00:43:32.760
I'm still buying
drinks on that one.

00:43:32.760 --> 00:43:33.370
Because I--

00:43:33.370 --> 00:43:34.268
[LAUGHTER]

00:43:34.268 --> 00:43:35.226
BOBBY BRAUN: All right.

00:43:35.226 --> 00:43:36.570
I can't wait to [INAUDIBLE].

00:43:36.570 --> 00:43:37.173
LEONARD DAVID: That
is not going to work!

00:43:37.173 --> 00:43:37.596
BOBBY BRAUN: Yeah.

00:43:37.596 --> 00:43:38.096
Yeah.

00:43:38.096 --> 00:43:41.330
LEONARD DAVID: And that
to me, that partnership

00:43:41.330 --> 00:43:45.680
that has to develop between
people in these missions

00:43:45.680 --> 00:43:49.220
to make things happen
is baton passing,

00:43:49.220 --> 00:43:51.320
space age baton passing.

00:43:51.320 --> 00:43:54.310
And each person
contributes to the whole.

00:43:54.310 --> 00:43:55.730
And it's pretty
amazing to watch.

00:43:59.740 --> 00:44:02.590
AUDIENCE: What work needs to
be done before we can actually

00:44:02.590 --> 00:44:03.775
send humans to Mars?

00:44:06.310 --> 00:44:08.050
STEPHEN PETRANEK: Not
much of anything--

00:44:08.050 --> 00:44:10.900
it's a problem of money.

00:44:10.900 --> 00:44:13.630
Musk estimates that
it's $36 billion--

00:44:13.630 --> 00:44:17.620
$35-36 billion to land
the first humans on Mars.

00:44:17.620 --> 00:44:19.000
He doesn't have $36 billion.

00:44:19.000 --> 00:44:22.690
If he did, I think he'd
probably start launching

00:44:22.690 --> 00:44:25.060
cargo missions this year.

00:44:25.060 --> 00:44:26.680
You need about
three cargo missions

00:44:26.680 --> 00:44:28.870
to land successfully on Mars.

00:44:28.870 --> 00:44:30.700
Bobby and a lot of
people from NASA

00:44:30.700 --> 00:44:34.780
think the first cargo landing
that SpaceX attempts on Mars

00:44:34.780 --> 00:44:36.460
will probably fail.

00:44:36.460 --> 00:44:39.970
And they think that
they will learn--

00:44:39.970 --> 00:44:41.440
BOBBY BRAUN: Not probably.

00:44:41.440 --> 00:44:42.910
STEPHEN PETRANEK:
Well, a lot of--

00:44:42.910 --> 00:44:44.740
a lot of people that
I've talked to at NASA

00:44:44.740 --> 00:44:47.369
seem to think it
will probably fail.

00:44:47.369 --> 00:44:49.410
BOBBY BRAUN: If you're
going to state my opinion,

00:44:49.410 --> 00:44:50.470
I'm going to jump in there.

00:44:50.470 --> 00:44:50.780
STEPHEN PETRANEK: All right.

00:44:50.780 --> 00:44:51.280
All right.

00:44:51.280 --> 00:44:53.800
BOBBY BRAUN: So what I've said
is that if you need three,

00:44:53.800 --> 00:44:54.676
you should send four.

00:44:54.676 --> 00:44:55.675
STEPHEN PETRANEK: Right.

00:44:55.675 --> 00:44:57.610
BOBBY BRAUN: Just before
you send the humans.

00:44:57.610 --> 00:44:59.170
Because one of them may--

00:44:59.170 --> 00:44:59.420
STEPHEN PETRANEK: May.

00:44:59.420 --> 00:45:00.253
BOBBY BRAUN: --fail.

00:45:00.253 --> 00:45:00.940
Go ahead.

00:45:00.940 --> 00:45:02.830
STEPHEN PETRANEK:
But anyway, there's

00:45:02.830 --> 00:45:05.830
a lot to be learned from
those failures, extraordinary.

00:45:05.830 --> 00:45:09.550
I mean, you probably learn, if
you have a successful landing

00:45:09.550 --> 00:45:13.640
and part of it is luck, that's
not a learning experience.

00:45:13.640 --> 00:45:16.690
If you have a failure and you
learn a lot from the failure,

00:45:16.690 --> 00:45:20.050
and then you don't make
the same mistakes again,

00:45:20.050 --> 00:45:22.430
things work a lot
better in the future.

00:45:22.430 --> 00:45:27.040
So what I suspect is going
to happen is that, as soon--

00:45:27.040 --> 00:45:30.610
if Tesla becomes as
successful as it should be,

00:45:30.610 --> 00:45:34.750
if Musk is able to launch
7,000 communications satellites

00:45:34.750 --> 00:45:39.060
and offer you data and voice
for $9.95 a month and capture--

00:45:39.060 --> 00:45:42.460
there are 10 billion
Wi-Fi connected devices

00:45:42.460 --> 00:45:44.260
on the planet, more
than there are people.

00:45:44.260 --> 00:45:47.590
If he gets a fourth of that
or a fifth of that population,

00:45:47.590 --> 00:45:50.500
two billion, and he gets
$10 a month from everybody,

00:45:50.500 --> 00:45:53.920
he's going to quickly have the
money to launch people to Mars.

00:45:53.920 --> 00:45:56.290
So this is really a
money problem and not

00:45:56.290 --> 00:45:58.060
a technology problem.

00:45:58.060 --> 00:46:01.880
Just as we threw money
at Apollo in the '60s,

00:46:01.880 --> 00:46:05.770
4% of the GDP of the United
States went into that program.

00:46:05.770 --> 00:46:09.637
Now about 1/16 of the GDP of the
United States goes into NASA.

00:46:09.637 --> 00:46:11.470
If you were to throw
those kind of resources

00:46:11.470 --> 00:46:13.450
into landing people
on Mars, there

00:46:13.450 --> 00:46:16.300
would definitely be people
on Mars within 10 years.

00:46:16.300 --> 00:46:18.010
AUDIENCE: So Elon
Musk has recently

00:46:18.010 --> 00:46:20.200
said that SpaceX
will land people

00:46:20.200 --> 00:46:22.910
on Mars in the next six years.

00:46:22.910 --> 00:46:25.390
What are your thoughts
on that timeline?

00:46:25.390 --> 00:46:27.310
As a subquestion,
what do you think

00:46:27.310 --> 00:46:30.410
is a more realistic
timeline for that to happen?

00:46:30.410 --> 00:46:32.680
STEPHEN PETRANEK: I think
they're kind of different.

00:46:32.680 --> 00:46:37.800
When I originally wrote my
book, Musk told me 2024, 2025.

00:46:37.800 --> 00:46:39.220
And I said come on.

00:46:39.220 --> 00:46:41.330
And he said, look.

00:46:41.330 --> 00:46:43.780
If we haven't landed
people on Mars by 2030,

00:46:43.780 --> 00:46:46.390
I will be deeply disappointed.

00:46:46.390 --> 00:46:48.310
And he meant deeply
disappointed,

00:46:48.310 --> 00:46:51.910
the kind of failure
that he doesn't accept.

00:46:51.910 --> 00:46:55.210
He recently walked
back his statement

00:46:55.210 --> 00:46:57.400
on when the first
humans would be on Mars.

00:46:57.400 --> 00:46:58.866
He recently said--

00:46:58.866 --> 00:47:00.490
I don't think many
people noticed this.

00:47:00.490 --> 00:47:04.360
But he was asked in an interview
when the first people would

00:47:04.360 --> 00:47:04.990
land on Mars.

00:47:04.990 --> 00:47:08.980
And he said the thing he's been
saying recently, which is 2024.

00:47:08.980 --> 00:47:12.160
And then he said,
well, at least I'm

00:47:12.160 --> 00:47:15.730
certain we'll have a
cargo mission by 2024.

00:47:15.730 --> 00:47:17.710
And that was a real walk back.

00:47:17.710 --> 00:47:19.360
Because he said
I'm not sure we'll

00:47:19.360 --> 00:47:23.020
have people on Mars in 2024,
which is what he's been saying.

00:47:23.020 --> 00:47:25.400
But I'm sure we'll
have a cargo mission.

00:47:25.400 --> 00:47:27.250
So give it a couple years.

00:47:27.250 --> 00:47:29.650
Maybe the first cargo
mission is 2026.

00:47:29.650 --> 00:47:32.200
Next cargo mission is 2028.

00:47:32.200 --> 00:47:34.940
Then 2030 you have
a cargo mission.

00:47:34.940 --> 00:47:38.640
And maybe simultaneously
you have two rockets going

00:47:38.640 --> 00:47:41.020
and you have a crew landing.

00:47:41.020 --> 00:47:43.890
That would be the estimate that
I would give you right now.

00:47:43.890 --> 00:47:46.810
LEONARD DAVID: There's
a catch-22 in all this,

00:47:46.810 --> 00:47:50.120
and it is the life
on Mars question.

00:47:50.120 --> 00:47:52.660
There's going to be,
probably, some new information

00:47:52.660 --> 00:47:54.520
about methane detection on Mars.

00:47:54.520 --> 00:47:59.860
And that's going to be a very
interesting possible connection

00:47:59.860 --> 00:48:01.566
for biology.

00:48:01.566 --> 00:48:02.940
The other thing
that's happening,

00:48:02.940 --> 00:48:06.310
and there's a lot of concern
about planetary protection

00:48:06.310 --> 00:48:10.510
and the coordination of
international groups.

00:48:10.510 --> 00:48:14.020
And Elon tossed his
Tesla out there.

00:48:14.020 --> 00:48:17.020
And that was not a happy moment
for the planetary protection

00:48:17.020 --> 00:48:24.380
people, although it didn't get
near Mars or some flew past it.

00:48:24.380 --> 00:48:26.900
But there was a problem.

00:48:26.900 --> 00:48:29.350
And there is a real--

00:48:29.350 --> 00:48:31.510
I think there's going
to be a headlong battle

00:48:31.510 --> 00:48:34.420
between planetary
protection people

00:48:34.420 --> 00:48:38.870
and the life detection people
and privatization of Mars.

00:48:38.870 --> 00:48:40.480
So I'd watch that one.

00:48:40.480 --> 00:48:41.950
That's going to come.

00:48:41.950 --> 00:48:45.220
And we'll see.

00:48:45.220 --> 00:48:48.190
But the lawyers thing
is the greatest.

00:48:48.190 --> 00:48:49.600
It's a head on collision.

00:48:49.600 --> 00:48:51.190
It's just going to be wild.

00:48:51.190 --> 00:48:53.530
I mean, it's the Wild
West sort of thing.

00:48:53.530 --> 00:48:57.760
But I think that's
going to be another one.

00:48:57.760 --> 00:48:59.200
I've just finished writing up.

00:48:59.200 --> 00:49:01.840
And I had to go talk
to a lot of lawyers.

00:49:01.840 --> 00:49:06.110
And you can have
the rolodex of pro,

00:49:06.110 --> 00:49:08.280
con, no, we shouldn't
do this and that.

00:49:08.280 --> 00:49:10.630
So we got some
real issues coming.

00:49:10.630 --> 00:49:13.180
ANTONIA JUHASZ: I mean, I
think the other issue that

00:49:13.180 --> 00:49:16.810
is being addressed in two
separate questions instead

00:49:16.810 --> 00:49:20.500
of one is this issue of where
the Outer Space Treaty was--

00:49:20.500 --> 00:49:23.560
a peace treaty was the intention
of it-- was a peace treaty.

00:49:23.560 --> 00:49:26.242
And how significantly more
advanced at this point

00:49:26.242 --> 00:49:27.700
weaponization of
space-- and money,

00:49:27.700 --> 00:49:29.320
when you're talking
about money--

00:49:29.320 --> 00:49:36.040
the US defense space
budget, so the space budget

00:49:36.040 --> 00:49:38.440
of the defense
industry, not NASA

00:49:38.440 --> 00:49:41.560
was $45 billion dollars the
last time it was identified,

00:49:41.560 --> 00:49:43.900
and that was in 2015.

00:49:43.900 --> 00:49:46.540
So there's a lot of money there.

00:49:46.540 --> 00:49:52.880
And then where and how is
the overlap being discussed

00:49:52.880 --> 00:49:56.920
as we move much more
quickly towards Mars

00:49:56.920 --> 00:49:59.740
and the amount of money
that's needed to do that?

00:49:59.740 --> 00:50:02.290
And where the money
currently resides,

00:50:02.290 --> 00:50:04.990
which is in the defense
industry and weaponization--

00:50:04.990 --> 00:50:08.540
will there be a marriage?

00:50:08.540 --> 00:50:13.860
That many people who for a long
time sought peace in space,

00:50:13.860 --> 00:50:16.807
you know, have fought to prevent

00:50:16.807 --> 00:50:18.890
LEONARD DAVID: That's why
we need the Space Force.

00:50:18.890 --> 00:50:19.280
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:50:19.280 --> 00:50:20.650
ANTONIA JUHASZ: That's why
we have the Space Force.

00:50:20.650 --> 00:50:22.191
BOBBY BRAUN: Let me
just-- before you

00:50:22.191 --> 00:50:23.930
jump on that, one
second-- so I'd just

00:50:23.930 --> 00:50:29.660
add that when you try to
define a timeline for when

00:50:29.660 --> 00:50:31.580
the first humans
will be on Mars,

00:50:31.580 --> 00:50:35.150
it depends a great deal
on what the strategy is

00:50:35.150 --> 00:50:36.690
for those humans.

00:50:36.690 --> 00:50:40.700
So it actually wouldn't
be that hard to just send

00:50:40.700 --> 00:50:44.780
a couple of humans to Mars, have
them be there for a few weeks,

00:50:44.780 --> 00:50:48.380
you know, a la Apollo, and
then have them come back.

00:50:48.380 --> 00:50:51.860
And we could certainly, as
a country, if we chose to,

00:50:51.860 --> 00:50:54.215
we could do that in the 2020s.

00:50:54.215 --> 00:50:55.840
STEPHEN PETRANEK:
But we would probably

00:50:55.840 --> 00:50:58.910
do an Apollo 8 kind of
thing and go into orbit

00:50:58.910 --> 00:51:00.800
and come back and
not actually land.

00:51:00.800 --> 00:51:02.300
BOBBY BRAUN: Well,
we could do both.

00:51:02.300 --> 00:51:03.258
STEPHEN PETRANEK: Yeah.

00:51:03.258 --> 00:51:06.800
BOBBY BRAUN: But in the series,
what we've chosen to do,

00:51:06.800 --> 00:51:11.600
if you notice, it's many of the
same astronauts from season one

00:51:11.600 --> 00:51:14.300
are still there in season two--

00:51:14.300 --> 00:51:16.980
Sammi, as an example.

00:51:16.980 --> 00:51:19.940
And so if you're thinking
about the first humans going

00:51:19.940 --> 00:51:23.570
to settle Mars, which is
the way SpaceX and Elon Musk

00:51:23.570 --> 00:51:27.110
talk about this, there
are many more cargo ships.

00:51:27.110 --> 00:51:29.330
There's much more of a
base camp environment that

00:51:29.330 --> 00:51:32.630
needs to be built up and
a lot more infrastructure.

00:51:32.630 --> 00:51:35.870
And so in my view, you're
talking about the 2030s

00:51:35.870 --> 00:51:38.750
by the time you would
send those humans because

00:51:38.750 --> 00:51:41.810
of all the emplacement
of the infrastructure

00:51:41.810 --> 00:51:43.950
that has to go first.

00:51:43.950 --> 00:51:45.330
LEONARD DAVID:
One good thing was

00:51:45.330 --> 00:51:49.190
when I got the word
to do this Mars book,

00:51:49.190 --> 00:51:53.310
I was at a conference
at Johnson Space Center.

00:51:53.310 --> 00:51:56.180
They brought in all
these scientists.

00:51:56.180 --> 00:51:58.340
And for the first
time in one room,

00:51:58.340 --> 00:52:00.770
people sat around and
talked about where do we--

00:52:00.770 --> 00:52:01.590
STEPHEN PETRANEK:
Where do we land?

00:52:01.590 --> 00:52:02.720
LEONARD DAVID: --yeah,
where do we land,

00:52:02.720 --> 00:52:04.280
and where can this base be?

00:52:04.280 --> 00:52:06.920
And then the exploration
zones were being drawn out.

00:52:06.920 --> 00:52:07.630
I mean--

00:52:07.630 --> 00:52:09.390
BOBBY BRAUN: There's been
real discussion of this.

00:52:09.390 --> 00:52:11.140
LEONARD DAVID: Yeah,
this is moving ahead.

00:52:11.140 --> 00:52:13.100
BOBBY BRAUN: There's
a question back here.

00:52:13.100 --> 00:52:14.516
AUDIENCE: So I
apologize if you're

00:52:14.516 --> 00:52:16.340
fed up with this question.

00:52:16.340 --> 00:52:18.740
Were you influenced at
all by Andy Weir's book,

00:52:18.740 --> 00:52:20.240
"The Martian" in the series?

00:52:20.240 --> 00:52:22.040
And then vise
versa, do you think

00:52:22.040 --> 00:52:24.500
he was influenced by your work?

00:52:24.500 --> 00:52:27.772
And what did you
think of the science?

00:52:27.772 --> 00:52:29.480
STEPHEN PETRANEK: I
have a personal story

00:52:29.480 --> 00:52:32.090
about that, which is in--

00:52:32.090 --> 00:52:35.330
my book came out in
2015, in July of 2015.

00:52:35.330 --> 00:52:42.450
In April of 2015, I had been
asked to do a TED talk on Mars.

00:52:42.450 --> 00:52:44.450
And I did this talk.

00:52:44.450 --> 00:52:47.550
I've done two other TED talks
on the main stage with TED.

00:52:47.550 --> 00:52:50.210
They were both greeted by
wild applause, and people

00:52:50.210 --> 00:52:52.460
standing up and everything.

00:52:52.460 --> 00:52:54.790
And this one was treated
with polite applause.

00:52:54.790 --> 00:52:56.540
And I walked off the
stage, and I thought,

00:52:56.540 --> 00:52:58.490
what the hell happened here?

00:52:58.490 --> 00:53:00.170
Jeff Bezos had a
dinner that night

00:53:00.170 --> 00:53:04.160
in which he basically tried to
criticize every single thing I

00:53:04.160 --> 00:53:06.530
had said about
people going to Mars,

00:53:06.530 --> 00:53:09.680
and how this was a PR
campaign by Elon Musk

00:53:09.680 --> 00:53:13.350
to gain more attention
for Tesla and so forth.

00:53:13.350 --> 00:53:16.010
And the people who ran TED--

00:53:16.010 --> 00:53:18.380
the guy who runs TED is
a close friend of mine--

00:53:18.380 --> 00:53:21.560
said we're not putting
your talk up online.

00:53:21.560 --> 00:53:26.270
And then in September,
"The Martian" came out.

00:53:26.270 --> 00:53:29.840
So my book came
out, wasn't selling.

00:53:29.840 --> 00:53:32.570
"The Martian" came out.

00:53:32.570 --> 00:53:35.330
I had sat down with
Charlie Bolden when

00:53:35.330 --> 00:53:38.450
I was writing the book and
talked about NASA's plans

00:53:38.450 --> 00:53:40.340
for humans landing on Mars.

00:53:40.340 --> 00:53:43.010
And he took me to one
of the 10,000 pages,

00:53:43.010 --> 00:53:46.550
obscure pages of NASA that
said in big bold type,

00:53:46.550 --> 00:53:49.490
NASA has no plans
for a human mission

00:53:49.490 --> 00:53:53.290
to Mars, right there
on their website.

00:53:53.290 --> 00:53:54.680
"Martian" comes out.

00:53:54.680 --> 00:53:57.230
All of a sudden, my book
starts selling like crazy.

00:53:57.230 --> 00:54:00.260
TED decides to put
my talk up online.

00:54:00.260 --> 00:54:03.560
Charlie Bolden appoints a
director of a manned mission

00:54:03.560 --> 00:54:04.130
to Mars.

00:54:04.130 --> 00:54:06.560
Didn't have any staff, but--

00:54:06.560 --> 00:54:13.700
so that's how much influence a
Hollywood movie had on society.

00:54:13.700 --> 00:54:17.810
It actually convinced people
that this was a possibility.

00:54:17.810 --> 00:54:19.430
If Matt Damon can
do it, we can do it.

00:54:19.430 --> 00:54:21.050
[LAUGHTER]

00:54:21.050 --> 00:54:23.600
ANTONIA JUHASZ: And
there is a dance remix

00:54:23.600 --> 00:54:25.737
of Stephen giving the TED talk.

00:54:25.737 --> 00:54:27.230
STEPHEN PETRANEK: Oh, God.

00:54:27.230 --> 00:54:28.820
BOBBY BRAUN: And
I'll also point out

00:54:28.820 --> 00:54:31.594
that Andy participated as
one of the big thinkers--

00:54:31.594 --> 00:54:32.510
STEPHEN PETRANEK: Yes.

00:54:32.510 --> 00:54:34.100
BOBBY BRAUN: --in season one.

00:54:34.100 --> 00:54:38.307
So he was a part of the first
season of the Nat Geo series.

00:54:38.307 --> 00:54:39.890
STEPHEN PETRANEK:
And I should mention

00:54:39.890 --> 00:54:42.650
that he's gone through kind
of a metamorphosis, too.

00:54:42.650 --> 00:54:48.470
He was very defensive
initially about the facts that

00:54:48.470 --> 00:54:50.360
were inaccurate in his book.

00:54:50.360 --> 00:54:53.270
Like 300 mile an
hour wind on Mars

00:54:53.270 --> 00:54:55.899
is not going to drive
a piece of an antenna

00:54:55.899 --> 00:54:57.440
through your spacesuit
kind of thing.

00:54:57.440 --> 00:55:00.600
In fact, you could walk through
a 300 mile an hour wind on Mars

00:55:00.600 --> 00:55:01.100
easily.

00:55:01.100 --> 00:55:04.400
It would be like a three
mile an hour wind on Earth.

00:55:04.400 --> 00:55:06.210
And he was very
defensive about that.

00:55:06.210 --> 00:55:09.590
And then he got
involved in season one.

00:55:09.590 --> 00:55:12.410
And you know, some
of us were kind

00:55:12.410 --> 00:55:15.140
of beating up on him
about that kind of stuff.

00:55:15.140 --> 00:55:16.970
And then season two came around.

00:55:16.970 --> 00:55:18.900
And we beat up on him some more.

00:55:18.900 --> 00:55:22.450
And now he's very open about
what was wrong in the book.

00:55:22.450 --> 00:55:23.700
BOBBY BRAUN: He's a great guy.

00:55:23.700 --> 00:55:24.726
STEPHEN PETRANEK:
He's a great guy.

00:55:24.726 --> 00:55:25.600
BOBBY BRAUN: Yeah.

